# App Settings

No magic involved, keeping it simple :)

+ PORT=3000 `sets the port`
+ START_SWAGGER=true `enables the open-api`
+ PRINT_ENV=true `logs the envs`

# Signin (superadmin)

On startup, if not exists, the user **superadmin** is created.  To change the default credentials you might want to set some envs:

+ `AUTH_MANAGER_USERNAME`
+ `AUTH_MANAGER_PASSWORD`
+ `AUTH_MANAGER_EMAIL`  

Otherwise you will need to signin and change those credentials at later time by using the REST API.

> ALWAYS treat your credentials with upmost care and store them somewhere safe!

# Roles And Permissions

There is four roles with different permissions:

+ superadmin `the config-manager god`
+ moderator `read/write - cannot elevate users (demigod)`
+ consumer `readonly - cannot signin, signout, refresh`
+ member `signin, signout, refresh`

> On signup the user gets the **member** role

# Session (powered by jwt)

By default a session expires after 15 minutes: `AUTH_MANAGER_ACCESS_TOKEN_TTL=900` (seconds).
A session can be refreshed for 7 days: `AUTH_MANAGER_REFRESH_TOKEN_TTL=604800` (seconds).
Once a session cannot be refreshed, the user is forced to signin again. To refresh a session the refresh token is used,
which generates a new access and refresh token pair.
Thus an active user can stay signed in infinitely or is forced to re-signin after 7 days of idling. The config-manager verifies the tokens by signing them with the `AUTH_MANAGER_TOKEN_SECRET`. A common misunderstanding is that a JWT is encrypted. It's not!

> NEVER store credentials in a JWT.

# Consumer Token

A consumer token is used by services, which don't need to authenticate but rather rely on some sort of an authorization. For example our config-manager is consumed by other microservices. Thus a microservice is not a **user** but a **consumer**! All it's interested in is fetch some configuration data and thus has no need for authentication. Funny thing is that the auth module in our config-manager is indeed a service which consumes the config module within the app. Henceforth it needs a consumer token which defaults to the `AUTH_MANAGER_PROVIDER_CONFIG_MANAGER_TOKEN`. It also requires the `AUTH_MANAGER_PROVIDER_CONFIG_MANAGER_BASE_URL` to be set. While you can safely ignore the url (it's an internal thingy), you should definitely provide your own consumer token. To achieve this simply start the config-manager, signin as the superadmin and create a plain consumer token. The consumer token does not need any additional settings or data. Finally shutdown the config-manager and update the token. On the next startup the new consumer token is used. Voil√†!

# Databases

The config-manager requires on a mongo and redis database to operate. It's a quite straight forward approach. Simply provide the credentials via the envs as show above in the [Getting Started](#getting-started) example.
